**Short version: yes, except in rare situations**

Mongo _ids have [&quot;a 4-byte value representing the seconds since the Unix epoch, a 5-byte random value, and a 3-byte counter, starting with a random value.&quot;](https://docs.mongodb.com/manual/reference/bson-types/#objectid) Each of these parts will normally (but not always) be ordered (the timestamp &amp; the counter) or constant (the 5 byte random value).

By default, mongo database drivers will generate `_id`s, so you can rely on those `_id`s having the same random value &amp; generally rely on the timestamp &amp; the counter moving forward. https://docs.mongodb.com/manual/core/document/

### The 4 byte timestamp

If you take a look at the [ObjectId generation code for node](https://github.com/mongodb/js-bson/blob/88a77466be/lib/objectid.js#L251), you can see that it&#39;s using `Date` to generate the initial timestamp portion of the ObjectId &amp; `Date` can go backwards when the clock updates. I&#39;d assume it&#39;s doing a similar thing on all of the drivers, so they&#39;d all likely have out-of-order _ids if you&#39;re doing an insert at the same time that the clock updates.

From testing, it seems like even if you [force server (i.e. database) generated ids](https://mongodb.github.io/node-mongodb-native/api-generated/mongoclient.html), `insertMany` with `ordered=false` will still preserve the _id ordering. Mongo doesn&#39;t do any sort of smearing on clock updates, so if there are any clock updates on the server that Mongo is running on, _ids might also be out of the order in the insertion array.


### The 5 byte random value

This should remain constant, but if you&#39;re having mongo (rather than the driver) generate the _ids &amp; there&#39;s a failover, I believe it will change. I&#39;m unsure how that&#39;d interact with inserts.

### The 3 byte counter

The 3 byte counter will reset after counting 2^24 (~16 million) documents. That means that if your driver (if _ids are being generated there) or mongo (if _ids are being generated there), reaches that point, documents inserted during that second in a bulk insert (either ordered or unordered) won&#39;t be ordered by _id.

### Mongo&#39;s `recordId`

Internally, mongo uses a [`recordId`](https://docs.mongodb.com/manual/reference/method/cursor.showRecordId/) rather than _id as its primary key. If you you do an unordered insert and look at the `recordIds`, `_ids` will be in the order that they were in the insertion array, but `recordIds` will be ordered in the order that they were actually inserted and won&#39;t match the _id ordering.

```
